{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534857"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:51:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:51:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.49,0.06,0.09,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97085"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11701"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97085"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of a painful lesion on her right hand. She works as a sheep farmer and recently assisted with shearing on her property. She has no significant medical history apart from type 2 diabetes mellitus, for which she takes metformin. She returned from a backpacking holiday in Vietnam three weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. On her right index finger, there is a 2 cm erythematous nodule with a central depression, surrounded by a red halo. The lesion is firm and painful to touch. There is mild lymphadenopathy in her right axilla.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Herpetic whitlow","Orf","Cat scratch disease","Mpox","Cutaneous anthrax"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a characteristic lesion of orf, also known as contagious ecthyma or contagious pustular dermatitis. The history of direct contact with sheep, particularly during shearing or lambing season, is highly suggestive of this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrf\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by a parapoxvirus that primarily affects sheep and goats. Humans become infected through direct contact with infected animals or fomites (inanimate objects that can carry and transmit infectious organisms, such as shearing equipment). The typical presentation is a solitary lesion on the hands or fingers that progresses through six stages: maculopapular, target, acute weeping, nodular, papillomatous, and finally regressive as it crusts and resolves. The lesion in this case appears to be in the nodular stage with its characteristic appearance of a firm nodule with central depression. Mild regional lymphadenopathy, as seen in this patient, is common. Patients are typically systematically well, though may present initially with a mild fever. Orf is usually self-limiting and resolves within 3-6 weeks without scarring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpetic whitlow\u003C/strong\u003E is a herpes simplex virus infection of the finger, typically presenting with grouped vesicles on an erythematous base that rupture to form painful erosions. While it can affect the fingers, it would not present as a single nodule with central depression. Additionally, the occupational exposure to sheep strongly favours orf.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECat scratch disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a papule or pustule at the inoculation site followed by regional lymphadenopathy. While lymphadenopathy is present in this case, the characteristic nodular lesion with central depression is not typical. Additionally, there is no history of cat exposure, which is the usual vector for this infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMpox\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar lesions, but typically has multiple lesions in various stages of development across the body. It is also associated with significant systemic symptoms, including fever, headache, and myalgia, which are absent in this patient. While Mpox should be considered in patients who have recently returned from at-risk international locations such as Vietnam, the clinical presentation in this case (solitary lesion, minimal systemic symptoms, clear occupational exposure to sheep) is not consistent with Mpox.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECutaneous anthrax\u003C/strong\u003E begins as a painless papule that evolves into a vesicle and then develops a characteristic black eschar. While it can be acquired through contact with infected animals, the lesion in this case is painful and lacks the characteristic eschar. Additionally, anthrax is rare in Australia, making orf a much more likely diagnosis given the patient\u0027s occupational exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Orf (contagious ecthyma) is a zoonotic parapoxvirus infection transmitted through direct contact with infected sheep or goats.","Orf typically presents as a solitary or few lesions on the hands that progress through stages from macule to papule to vesicle to pustule before crusting.","Systemic symptoms are usually mild or absent in orf infection, though regional lymphadenopathy may occur."],"references":["Orf. The Australasian College of Dermatologists. 2019. Available at: https://www.dermcoll.edu.au/atoz/orf/","Kassa T. A Review on Human Orf: A Neglected Viral Zoonosis. Res Rep Trop Med. 2021 Jul 8;12:153-172. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8275206/","Seol S. Cat Scratch Disease. In: DermNet [online]. 2024; cited 2025 Apr 2. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/catscratch-disease"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T15:48:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T15:49:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97085"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0